<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06029179 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06029179 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; DeLong  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  LOS-ALTOS-HILLS; APPOINTMENT; CITY; MANAGER  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Richard B. &quot;Dick&quot; DeLong, retired city manager of San Mateo, becomes actingcity manager of Los Altos Hills next month.;    DeLong, 60, will replaceThomas Frutchey, who became city manager of Campbell on Monday.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LOS ALTOS HILLS NAMES ACTING CITY MANAGER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Until DeLong assumes the post Feb. 11, Bill Ekern, public works director,will be city manager pro tem.;    A search for a permanent city manager isplanned, Sid Hubbard, mayor pro tem, said Monday.;    &quot;I'm looking forward toit,&quot; DeLong said Monday. &quot;I think it will be exciting. I met the people atCity Hall the other day and they seem like a good crew.;    &quot;I intend to meetwith each of the city council members over the next few weeks, and then I'llhave a better idea of what their priorities are.&quot;;    Hubbard said, &quot;I thinkit's an excellent selection. He's had many years (of experience) both inMountain View and San Mateo, and I think his perspective on the town will bevery valuable.&quot;;    DeLong was city manager of San Mateo from 1976 until March1990, when Arne Croce, former city manager of Los Altos, was appointed to thepost.;    Previously, DeLong was city manager of Mountain View from 1973 to1976 and city manager of Milpitas from 1962 to 1973.;    He served aspresident of the City Managers' Department of the League of California Citiesin 1986-'87 and was a member of the league's board of directors from 1988 to1990.;    He is a graduate of the University of Denver, where he earned abachelor of arts degree in political science and a master of science ingovernment management.;    The San Mateo resident is married and has twomarried daughters.;    The Southern California recruiting firm of NormanRoberts and Associates will search for a new city manager, said Roberts, whosecompany is being paid $12,000 for the effort.;    Roberts said Monday that ajob description is being finalized and his firm soon will begin recruitingcandidates.;    He said he hopes the city council will be able to interviewfinalists by April and that a new city manager can be on the job by May.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DON BRIGNOLO, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910129  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  354  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday January 29, 199100029179,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>